"One of our roles is to provide the Commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
To date, the Commission has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," Mikulka added.
Australia's success, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater holdings, has recently seen a global resounding.
New Zealand, too, gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which was assigned to it by the commission last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which is the extent of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefits they will reap in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they project, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their requests.
They can do so within ten years after they have ratified the "Montego Bay Convention".
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the zone of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this zone is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, we are not mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," Mikulka said, exaggerating the director, adding that "their areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime is anchored in a contract."
