The next morning, after a ten-and-a-half-hour journey, shaken on noisy rails whose cadence reminded me of the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived in the Turkish capital – presented as a new city of a new century-old state, turning its back on its German past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, is an example of a change in Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra modern structure, expressly built in stone and steel, in a developing district, surrounded by semi-constructed shopping centers and many pastries in which the middle managers in costume-ties-men and women- meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Costume, tie and he even has a Black Berry.
The aim of this foreign policy is to now reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its back country.
Now she has to look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for either of them.
She had to do both.
“But then, at some point, I asked if Turkey shouldn’t choose.”
“Turkey,” he said, “does not want to have to choose between the two.”
