Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry into its roundtable of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan's first bank, which will disburse nine billion dollars to take 21% of its capital, a new one welcomed by a sharp decline in its stock market price.
A week after unveiling a provisional agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s ordinary shares at a unit price of $25.25, a total of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, or 28% above its current price.
Morgan Stanley’s stock, however, lost 6.79% at $23.07 around 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s chief executive officer.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to diversify its activities but put it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been changed in recent days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, "we thought that the participation would be composed entirely of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley shares 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares within a year if they are exchanged more than 50% above the conversion price, or at about $47, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley said MUFG's capital will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A group spokeswoman, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" lightened its balance sheet since late August.
The last few weeks have been arduous for the group, which saw its stock market price slump by half as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt hovered.
This cost rebounded on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of major Wall Street investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, he was the third to put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit polling stations and an account by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad "yes" victory, placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft constitution in the night of Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly," he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place quietly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), concerned a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies that its emigrants send.
Supported by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived around 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at al-Maza military base, docked at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, on board helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in "good health," and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this hostage group had been sacked from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Egyptian agency, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
“An exchange of shots has occurred, and half of the kidnappers have been killed, the others fleeing,” said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "blitz" unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our secret service, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle on which the kidnappers were, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is at the forefront of the current election campaign.
All the better.
But one aspect of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will rise up to denounce the sums of misery that are given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that are starving?
Which politician will dare remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is devoting three and a half million euros to the restoration of the only Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of the Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected representatives and all government departments, and this, in consultation.
In Quebec, the Federation of Quebec History Societies, at least 40,000 volunteers in 211 history, heritage, archival and genealogy societies are concerned with exploring history, preserving with three under private archival mounds and preserving archaeological remains.
They are often the watchdogs of our heritage, protesting with the energy of despair when promoters and decision-makers launch their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
When, a tribune for history and heritage?
The governments of the Benelux nationalize a part of the bank Fortis
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries are supporting, with a sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution as well.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourgish and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this issue, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been escalating for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank. In a certain sense, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy almost half (up 49%) of the bank’s capital in each of the countries.
The bank is undoubtedly going to sell some of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the activities, mainly insurance, that it acquired last year from the Dutch organization ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
Only on Friday, the company’s shares fell 12 percent, to its lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>14 billion, which, according to the company's leaders, is not realistic.
The company’s management accuses the uncertainty of the over-Atlantic, related to the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout plan, of being at the root of the crash of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the substance.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they will not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the customer circle of the bank and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information about the prescription of medicines, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it means entrusting your chicken to a fox," Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital dependent on the health of the client, and if they feel that the risk is too high, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after becoming aware of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides himself with pharmacies, data about the purchase of drugs of the person in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol lowering, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk factor, so there is not much left to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, minor problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or against hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are constrained by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses, linking them with data on drug use, and are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is also becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to broaden the scope of government control over companies specializing in data provision is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus, and ultimately, chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside the other problems, largely global.
Today, a France-India summit will also take place, where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be the main issue.
The European Union recognizes that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given a broader right to speak in international affairs, but member countries have not yet managed to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They were not too late on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double the good trade of a hundred.
Given that trade in goods has increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this does not appear to be an overly ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, so that air traffic can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this subject was discussed.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both play a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate agenda, including that it would like to reduce its toxic emissions by at least twenty per cent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, along with the fact that a global market would have to pass at the climate conference scheduled next year, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They also wished to prevent food prices from rising, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is on his way to the French capital today, where he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the news agency, the agreement would last for 15 years.
