Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau 3,000 meters above sea level in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or near the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Safety (Ntsb) said that a team of investigators sent to the scene a few hours after the wreckage was spotted, they identified the aircraft: the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal belongings were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name of Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
By the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had traveled the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters in height, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertisement you're not expecting.
An unusual 4x4 of an original and well-defined design, with marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
Here, in summary, Glk, the last born of the "compact" off-road of the house of the star, with which Mercedes-Benz tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
Due to its out-of-the-box, unexpected and unconventional content will be the communication that will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in the Mercedes-Benz showrooms, from October 17th.
Thus, the advertising battle that will accompany the start of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automobile brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, which will dominate the heart of Milan's shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication provides for the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, we will have the impression that when looking at the image, the car comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of innovative technology ELIMA8, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recompose into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertising, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
Will it succeed in attracting the interest of future acquirers with this formula? We will see.
